# CLAUDE.md (router example)

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This is an EXAMPLE router, not a file to copy verbatim.
# It shows the shape: a few always-on inline rules at the top, then a set of
# "trigger lines" that point to external rule files loaded only when relevant.
# Replace every <PLACEHOLDER> with your own value during install, and delete
# any section that does not apply to you.
# See docs/01-concepts.md for the reasoning behind this layout.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Always-on rules (inline)

These are short and apply to essentially every session, so they live here.

- Language: respond in <YOUR_LANGUAGE>.
- Tone: <YOUR_TONE — e.g. concise and direct / careful and explanatory>.
- Never do <YOUR_HARD_PROHIBITION — e.g. force-push to the main branch> without explicit confirmation.

## 2. Triggered rules (loaded on demand)

Each entry below is a pointer. The full rule lives in an external file and is
read only when its trigger situation arises — keeping this router small.

A good trigger names a concrete situation with a clear on/off boundary: broad
enough to fire whenever the rule matters, narrow enough that it does not load on
every turn. "Writing SQL migrations" is a usable trigger; "working on the
backend" is too broad to save anything.

### Coding standards
> Trigger: writing or reviewing <YOUR_STACK> code — not docs, config, or one-off scripts.
> Read: rules/common/coding-style.md

### Protected paths (absolute — hook-enforced)
> Trigger: any write/edit operation. The paired hook enforces this regardless.
> Read: rules/personal/critical/protect-paths.md

### Feature workflow
> Trigger: starting a new feature, bug fix, or refactor.
> Read: rules/personal/workflow/feature-workflow.md

### Device & environment
> Trigger: file transfer, SSH, network drive, or path-specific work across machines.
> Read: rules/personal/environment/devices.md
> Note: only relevant if you sync ~/.claude/ across multiple devices. Delete this
> entry entirely if you use a single machine.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Add a new trigger line here whenever you move a heavy or situational rule out
# of this router into its own file. Keep this file small on purpose.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
